      "Tokoloshe in the Night keeps the local sense of fear, night, or threshold alive without reducing it to one neat plotline. It draws attention to how people remember where not to go, what not to ignore, and how danger is pictured. The story's hold comes from recurring motifs of warning and boundary, not from boilerplate suspense. What remains is the feeling that certain edges of the world are never entirely empty."
