      "The Selkie Bride is best understood within the storytelling traditions of Scotland in Northern Europe. It stays anchored in warning, boundary, and fear rather than in a single fixed version. It is most useful as a guide to the themes of warning, boundary, and fear. That keeps the story tied to landscape, community, and transmission from the start.",
      "As a creature legend, the story is strongest where warning, boundary, and fear define a zone of warning. The being matters because it makes a boundary feel inhabited, risky, or morally charged. Such tales often survive through repeated caution, not through one universally fixed storyline. That is why place and atmosphere matter as much as named action.",
      "The Selkie Bride keeps the local sense of fear, night, or threshold alive without reducing it to one neat plotline. It draws attention to how people remember where not to go, what not to ignore, and how danger is pictured. The story's hold comes from recurring motifs of warning and boundary, not from boilerplate suspense. What remains is the feeling that certain edges of the world are never entirely empty."
